16. The meaning probably is ‘what are masters (owners) to do when thieves are so bold ?’ i. e. as you were when you stole the goat. ' Others take fureszservz', according to comic usage, and translate, ‘what treatment may I expect from the master, when a mere slave dares to revile me thus? ’ But this is somewhat forced.

29, 30. vitulam for vaccam. The next line is from Theoc. 1. 26, where the animals mentioned are a goat with two kids. Virgil has not improved upon his original, for cows (as Keightley observes) seldom have twins. In G. 3. 176 he discountenances the practice of milking cows in calving time.

31. depono, ‘lay,‘ of a wager. But the simple ponere (1. 36) is more generally used. So θέμεν Theoc. 5. 21.
